<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870409-0167 </DOCNO><HL> Letters to the Editor:U.S. PresidentsWith Star Quality</HL><DD> 04/09/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   In his March 25 back-page article on Alexander Haig's candidacy for president, David Shribman noted that Mr. Haig &quot;is hoping to follow the path that George Washington, Andrew Jackson, William Henry Harrison, Ulysses Grant and Dwight Eisenhower took from general's stars to civilian commander in chief. It was a destination also reached by his secretary-of-state predecessors James Monroe, James Madison and John Quincy Adams.&quot;    Mr. Shribman left out at least one general who became president, Zachary Taylor, as well as three secretaries of state who attained the White House: Thomas Jefferson, Martin Van Buren and James Buchanan.    Dan Harrison   Briarcliff Manor, N.Y.   ---   During 40 years of service in the U.S. Army, &quot;Old Rough and Ready&quot; Zachary Taylor was promoted to major general and commanded the Army of the Rio Grande during the Mexican War, defeating Gen. Santa Anna at the Battle of Buena Vista.    G.W. Boxall   Atlanta   ---   Since Gen. Haig made his announcement in New Hampshire, it is too bad that its native son, Franklin Pierce, was forgotten in the list of generals who made it to the White House. Pierce was a general in the Mexican War prior to his one term as president (1853-1857).    About him the partisans of Gen. Winfield Scott, who unsuccessfully opposed Pierce as a Whig, wrote:    &quot;Some think that Frank's a fighting man,    And some think that he is not.   'Tis said that when in Mexico,    While leading on his force,   He took a sudden fainting fit,    And tumbled off his horse.&quot;   Edward Jackson Bennett   Member, New Hampshire House of Representatives    Concord, N.H.</TEXT></DOC>